	 (157,50,0,'@Beska unfortunately, i cannot provide any external source.  This is something that has come to me after watching quite a lot of anime over the years.','2012-12-12 01:44:13',NULL,46,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (158,50,0,'@CamiloMartin I am not familiar with that particular anime, although looking it up on wikipedia tells me it doesn''t really hold any interest for me. I don''t like slice of lifes (lives?). Though it could be explained as pretty clear lampshading, as the creator took a seemingly unrelated/non-justified trope, and used it specifically to point out what the trope signifies.  Think about how many expressive/mobile hair examples you see, conveying emotion/distress/mood/whatever (ed''s little spike from FMA, LOTS of Moe...) and then an exception to the ''expressive but non-useful'' trope (Bobobobobobobo)','2012-12-12 01:48:30',NULL,46,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (159,94,1,'Perhaps it''s like Zen, where going into deeper and deeper mental states you achieve a greater knowledge and understanding about the Truth behind the world and the Laws that underlie everything, but such knowledge cannot be expressed in words and must be "experienced to be believed".','2012-12-12 01:49:30',NULL,97,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (160,111,6,'Perhaps Hiroshi Gamo was an inspiration for Ohba, so this was his way of paying homeage.','2012-12-12 01:51:58',NULL,97,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (161,129,0,'And I haven''t read the light-novels so I don''t know if it''s clarified in them. But like other shows, it''s entirely possible for the rules to be slightly different between Manga/Novels and Anime.','2012-12-12 01:55:01',NULL,17,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (162,121,1,'@KenLi Nobody else did it, so I made a meta question for this question: http://meta.anime.stackexchange.com/questions/69/should-we-allow-questions-that-are-about-japanese-language-use-in-anime-manga','2012-12-12 01:59:17',NULL,24,'CC BY-SA 3.0');
