	 (206,76,0,'@Morpheus: Nah, I only do it as a joke. I''ll stop now :P','2012-12-12 05:01:54',NULL,27,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (207,133,0,'@Krazer On the same page you linked, there is this sentence: "First, if he fell as a red player, he wouldn''t be able to continue staying in the guild and the clearing group." Also this sentence: "In a certain sense, they were the biggest enemy of the clearing group, bigger than the boss monsters, the red players." There are a few more but I''m sure two will suffice. Just search for "red player".','2012-12-12 05:09:39',NULL,107,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (208,106,0,'@acolyte: Correct, you explained it better than I could. As for your spoiler addition, I''ll edit my answer further today.','2012-12-12 05:17:48',NULL,27,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (209,133,2,'@atlantiza PK guilds and players in SAO are dubbed "Red" by players to differentiate them from normal criminals, because their cursor color is also orange. If you read up a bit more for the paragraph I noted you''ll see that Johnny Black (a ["red" player](http://swordartonline.wikia.com/wiki/Category:Red_Players)) had a orange cursor.','2012-12-12 05:21:15',NULL,63,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (210,144,0,'Chaotic-good alignment basically says "does what he wants, follows his own free will", so they''re not necessarily *good* as perceived by everyone else. Also, it may be based on the alignment of the person that became a heroic spirit.','2012-12-12 05:22:23',NULL,20,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
	 (211,144,1,'Gilgamesh was also Chaotic Good and he was both a jerk and an ass.','2012-12-12 05:36:13',NULL,63,'CC BY-SA 3.0'),
